            <div class="sectionTextLeft">
              <p>
                But as I said, I do wear sunglasses a lot also. My eyes are quite sensitive to the light so I'll honestly wear 
                them on all but the greyest of days. I have two pairs to recommend here. The first is more a brand than a pair - 
                choose the pair that suit your style, but the lenses are <em>fantastic</em>. The brand is called 
                <a href="https://www.sungod.co/en-gb/">Sungod</a> and their 8KO polarised lenses are brilliant.
              </p>
              <p>
                Sungod have several colours of lenses and each one lets a different amount of light through and has a different 
                tint (there's a good lens guide on each product page on their website). They also have two lens classes - 4KO
                and 8KO with 8KO being the newer technology. Each of those then comes in either polarised or non-polarised. 
                I've never tried the 4KO but the 8KO are simply amazing - I've never 
                looked through a cleaner, crisper lens, including Oakley and Maui Jim (in my opinion).
              </p>
              <p>
                I'm partial to the 8KO polarised Smoke lens, personally. Smoke is basically their version of black or grey.
                It has 14% light transmission, which I find just about perfect. Light transmission is the amount of light the 
                lens lets through - although these days it's not the only factor since a lot of lenses cut out different amounts
                of light from different parts of the colour spectrum. So a 14% lens means it lets 14% of visible light through, 
                which for my eyes is just right. Most normal sunglasses will have a VLT (Visible Light Transmission) of anywhere 
                from 8-15%. Ray Ban's original lens and I think still the most popular is their G-15 which is green and has 15% 
                VLT. Oakley's black prizm polarized lens has 12% VLT. Getting the right balance for your eyes is important here.
                Too high a VLT and they won't do their job well, too low a VLT (too dark) and you'll struggle to see into shadow
                from a lighted area (you'll probably strugle with this regardless to be honest) and you'll struggle when the 
                sun suddenly goes behind a cloud or you walk into an area in shadow.
              </p>
              <p>
                But as I say, everyone is different and really the only way to know your preference is to try for yourself.
                Sungod's slate lens is a very good starting point, though. Also I should note they offer a lifetime guarantee
                on their frames - they're near indestructable but if you ever do manage to destroy them just send them 
                back and they'll repair or replace them. Only the frames though, which is unfortunate as the lenses are
                definitely the part you will damage eventually. That being said, their anti-scratch coating is better than 
                most I've come across and while they're nowhere close to scratch-<em>oroof</em> they are a bit mnore 
                scratch-<em>resistant</em> than other lenses, I'm fairly certain.
              </p>
              
