            <h3>My White Cane</h3>
            <p>
            The short version: I wrapped some reflective white tape around a hiking pole and called it an invention.
            </p>
            <p>
              With a bit more detail: I bought the same 
              <a href="https://shop.rnib.org.uk/white-reflective-tape-for-canes-1-metre-3304">reflective white tape</a>
              used on regular white canes from RNIB and a fully collapsible hiking pole and paired the two together, 
              which resulted in a white cane that can support my body weight should I stumble.
            </p>
            <p>
              The tape is designed to repair white canes (which are themselves aluminium canes wrapped in this tape) and
              sold by the metre. The walking pole I have is 120cm long (including the handle) so you need just over one 
              piece. At the time of writing it costs £3.20 (exc. VAT) oer metre, and is VAT_exempt if you are blind or 
              partially sighted, or buying on behalf of a blind of partially sighted person.
            </p>
            <p>
              The cane is the trickier and much more expensive part. I took a gamble on spending the money and it paid off.
            </p>
            <p>
              Originally I did so because I go hiking and walking and do so with a pole (and due to be <em>very</em> unsure
              of my footing on uneven ground I consider it an absolute necessity), but when walking in more congested areas 
              such as the New Forest, I felt I needed a white cane as well to let other people know I couldn't see very 
              well and possibly wouldn't see them to allow them to take this into consideration. Thus, this idea was born.
            </p>
            <p>
              But it ended up being for far more than just hiking. In my everyday life I'm fine walking on a oath - the 
              ocassional pothole aside - but if I want to do something as simple as cut across some grass then this becomes 
              trickier than you would think because of the nature of my sight loss. Being essentially blind in one eye 
              means no depth percention, no depth perception means you can't really see things like small rises and falls 
              in the ground level, and when the ground is suddenly six inches further down than you naturally expect, 
              a stumble is inevitable. And mostly that's fine, if a bit unnerving, but ocassionally you could fall over 
              and potentially hurt yourself.
            </p>
            <p>
              Then there's the blind spots in my vision - I can focus mostly fine on a specific spot, but only on a 
              <em>very</em> specific spot, and I will not necessarily see what is right next to it. This means if there's 
              a small hole from an animal (or in one instance a rather deep hole from a missing fence post where I quite
              seriously hurt my ankle) then I may well not see them. And that's where the pole comes in.
            </p>
            <p>
            It's not going to save you every time, but it does quite a lot of the time, and much more importantly, it gives 
            you (or at least me) the confidence to know you can walk across less than ideal terrain - and I mean in the 
            middle of a town here, not just out in the wilds - and emerge unscathed on the other side.
            </p>
            <p>
              Now the pole you use is very important. Most hiking poles these days are telescopic, and that's no good if 
              you want a collapsible cane. Once the you put the tape around one of the sections, it will no longer 
              fit inside another section, since they are originally sized to only just fit and the tape makes them too 
              wide. This rules out a large number of canes.
            </p>
            <p>
              Fortunately, there are also collapsible canes, although most modern versions of these will also not work.
              These are canes that are a specific length (and cannot be adjusted in length) and which fold into three 
              or four sections. However, many of these are unsuitable because they have a telescopic locking mechanism - 
              that is to say, you put all the parts together and then push down on the top part of the cane proper whilst 
              pulling up on the handle and part of the cane slides out of the handle and this is how you lock the cane 
              together. But for the same reason as the telescopic cane this will not work because applying white tape 
              will stop the cane moving into the handle thus meaning you can never collapse it. You could apply the tape 
              to all but the top part, but that part is usually quite big and it would look odd.
            </p>
            <p>
            However, I have found one brand of cane that is fully collapsible with no telescoping. I would imagine others 
            exist, and hopefully even cheaper versions, but I can't be sure and it's quite hard to tell. I bought a pair 
            for about £20 of Amazon originally that made no mention of telescoping, but they had the same telescoping locking
            mechanism. So the only ones I can be sure will work are the ones I have and that's the 
            <a href="https://ultralightoutdoorgear.co.uk/trail-blaze-poles/">Mountain King Trail Blaze Poles</a>
            As I said, they are unfortunately expensive, at the time of writing the retail for £90 (and those are actually 
            the cheapest poles Mountain King make!) but if you also use them as hiking poles then it is probably a justifiable
            cost. I, personally, am very glad I did it.
            </p>
            <p>
              I don't really know how much I need to say about the actual process. Buy the poles, buy the tape, apply the tape.
              Definitely not rocket science. You can apply the tape length-ways (as opposed to spiralling it round), it is 
              wide enough. The only thing I would say is to try to be precise trimming the ends of the tape, because if it 
              overlaps the joins then the pole will not fit together. But at the same time you don't want to end the tape 
              before the join particularly, otherwise you will have weird visible rings marring the whiteness of your cane
              and it will look odd.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-6 ">
        <div class="ulContainer" style="width:50%; text-align:left; margin:7rem 0 0 5rem;">
          <h5>Important Notes:</h5>
          <ul>
            <li>It must be a collapsible cane, not a telescopic one. With telescopic, the tape makes it too wide for the 
              sections to slide inside one another.
            </li>
            <li>
              Many collapsible canes also have a telescopic element nowdays. This would mean you could not make the whole
              cane white. The cane I've linked is the only one I know is fully collapsible.
            </li>
            <li>
              The white tape is sold by the metre. You can put it on length ways, so two metres should be more than ample.
            </li>
            <li>
              Make sure to trim the tape carefully. Overlapping the join can stop the sections snapping into place.
            </li>
            <li>
              If you get the cane I recommend, the rubber tips on the bottom are basically useless - they develop holes very
               quickly - but you can buy good ones at cheap prices from ebay.
            </li>
            <li>
              The main downside of this is the rubber tip makes it hard/impossible to tap the cane on the ground like with 
              a plastic-tip cane. The rubber sticks to the ground. A trade off I think is worth paying, but be warned.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>


      </div>
